data.content:
# .NET Framework → .NET 8 Migration: BackgroundProcessor

## Critical Breaking Changes

1. **`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** in .NET 8 — it's completely removed
2. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` also throws** — the entire abort mechanism is gone
3. **`ThreadAbortException` is never raised** — your catch block is dead code

## Why It Was Removed

`Thread.Abort()` was inherently unsafe — it could fire between any two IL instructions, corrupting locks, leaving resources half-disposed, and causing subtle data loss. .NET Core/8 replaced it with **cooperative cancellation**.

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Task? _workerTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass token so blocking calls can be interrupted
                var item = await GetNextItemAsync(token);
                await ProcessItemAsync(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Graceful shutdown requested — roll back partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break;
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public async Task StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerTask is null)
            return;

        timeout ??= TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5);

        // Signal cooperative cancellation
        await _cts.CancelAsync();  // .NET 8+ API, thread-safe

        // Wait with a hard deadline — no Thread.Abort needed
        if (await Task.WhenAny(_workerTask, Task.Delay(timeout.Value)) != _workerTask)
        {
            // Worker didn't stop in time — log warning, but don't force-kill
            // (there is no safe equivalent of Abort)
            Log.Warning("Worker did not stop within timeout");
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _cts?.Cancel();
        _workerTask?.Wait(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## Key Migration Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Details |
|---|---|
| **Blocking `GetNextItem()`** | If this blocks on a `Queue.Dequeue` or socket, cancellation won't interrupt it. Migrate to `Channel<T>`, `BlockingCollection.Take(token)`, or async I/O. |
| **Fire-and-forget `Task.Run`** | Unobserved exceptions silently vanish. Always `await _workerTask` in `StopAsync`. |
| **`CancellationTokenSource` not disposed** | It allocates a `WaitHandle`—always dispose it. |
| **`volatile bool` still compiles** | It "works" but can't interrupt blocking calls. `CancellationToken` can. |
| **`Thread.Sleep` → `Task.Delay`** | `Thread.Sleep` blocks a thread pool thread. Use `await Task.Delay(ms, token)`. |

## If You Can't Make `GetNextItem` Async

Use `BlockingCollection<T>` which accepts a `CancellationToken`:

```csharp
private readonly BlockingCollection<WorkItem> _queue = new();

private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
{
    // GetConsumingEnumerable checks the token on each iteration
    foreach (var item in _queue.GetConsumingEnumerable(token))
    {
        ProcessItem(item);
    }
}
```

## For Long-Running CPU Work

If `ProcessItem` is CPU-bound and long, check the token periodically inside it:

```csharp
void ProcessItem(WorkItem item, CancellationToken token)
{
    foreach (var chunk in item.Chunks)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
        ProcessChunk(chunk);
    }
}
```

**Bottom line:** Replace the `Abort` hammer with cooperative `CancellationToken` checks at every point that should be interruptible. There is no .NET 8 equivalent of force-killing a thread — by design.
